# Frontend Access Control Template

## Generation Goal
- Generate reusable access-control building blocks for enterprise dashboards.
- Support route-level and action-level authorization with consistent permission checks.

## Required Artifacts
- `features/auth/types/permission.ts`
- `features/auth/lib/permission-matrix.ts`
- `features/auth/lib/can.ts`
- `components/auth/RoleGuard.tsx`
- `components/auth/PermissionGuard.tsx` (optional but recommended)
- `hooks/usePermission.ts`

## Permission Model
- Use explicit permission keys, for example:
  - `USER_READ`
  - `USER_WRITE`
  - `ORDER_APPROVE`
  - `PAYMENT_REFUND`
- Keep role-to-permission mapping centralized in `permission-matrix.ts`.
- Avoid hardcoded role checks scattered across feature components.

## Guard Pattern
- Use `RoleGuard`/`PermissionGuard` wrappers for conditional rendering.
- Support both:
  - hide UI when unauthorized
  - disable actions with clear UX feedback
- Do not mix authorization logic directly into complex UI trees.

## Route-Level Authorization
- Add route-level checks in layout/page guards where applicable.
- Redirect unauthorized users to safe fallback pages.
- Keep route policy and action policy consistent.

## Action-Level Authorization
- Enforce permission checks for:
  - create/edit/delete actions
  - approve/reject operations
  - export/download sensitive data
- Pair UI-level checks with backend enforcement; frontend guard is not security boundary alone.

## Template Safety Rules
- Never trust only client-side authorization.
- Never expose privileged actions without permission checks.
- Keep permission names stable and documented for team consistency.
